.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Malherbe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, French, Huguenot: locative name from the canton of Malesherbes (Loiret) in France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Malherbe II was born about 1135, in Appleby, Lincolnshire, England, his father, John de Malherbe I, was 27 and his mother, Amabel De Le Mare, was 27. He married Matilda FitzSwain in 1160, in Silkstone, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1181, in Silkstone, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1135–1181":"umbes 1135–1181","1131–1158":"1131–1158","1135–1181":"1135–1181","1136–1181":"1136–1181","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1175–1216":"1175–1216","1178–1246":"1178–1246","1110–1181":"1110–1181","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","about 1181":"umbes 1181","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1110":"1110","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1131":"1131","1160":"